# Development Standards for AI Agents

<version>1.0.0</version>

## Context
- When implementing new features or modifying existing code
- When writing tests
- When creating components or services
- When working with state management
- When handling user interactions

## Requirements

### TypeScript Strict Mode
- Always use explicit types (no implicit any)
- Always check for null/undefined before accessing properties
- Never use `any` type unless absolutely necessary
- Use interfaces or type aliases for complex types
- Enable strict mode in tsconfig.json

### Factory Pattern Usage
- Always access services via factory methods
- Never directly instantiate services in components
- Import from factory files: `AuthServiceFactory.ts`, `CouponServiceFactory.ts`, `RoleServiceFactory.ts`
- Use factories to get service instances: `getCouponService()`

### Component Structure
- Use functional components with hooks
- Define interfaces for props: `interface ComponentProps { }`
- Use TypeScript for component type: `const Component: React.FC<Props> = () => { }`
- Destructure props in function signature
- Keep components focused on single responsibility
- Use hooks in this order: useState → useEffect → useCallback → useMemo

### Service Layer
- Implement business logic in services, not components
- Validate input in services before data operations
- Check permissions in services
- Return consistent error messages
- Use async/await for all service methods
- Handle errors with try-catch and re-throw with context

### Test-Driven Development (TDD)
- Write failing tests first (RED)
- Implement minimal code to pass tests (GREEN)
- Refactor while keeping tests passing (REFACTOR)
- Use AAA pattern: Arrange → Act → Assert
- Test behavior, not implementation details
- Mock external dependencies

### Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (`CouponList`)
- Hooks: use + PascalCase (`useCoupons`)
- Services: PascalCase (`CouponService`)
- Factories: PascalCase + Factory (`CouponServiceFactory`)
- Types/Interfaces: PascalCase (`Coupon`)
- Variables: camelCase (`userId`)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (`MAX_RETRIES`)

### Package Management
- Use pnpm for all operations
- Never use npm or yarn
- Run commands from project root (no cd)
- Use standard pnpm commands: `pnpm test`, `pnpm build`, `pnpm dev`

## Examples

<example>
// ✅ Good: Using factory pattern
import { getCouponService } from '../services/CouponServiceFactory';
const service = getCouponService();

// ✅ Good: Explicit types
const formatDate = (date: string, locale: string = 'en-US'): string => {
  return new Date(date).toLocaleDateString(locale);
};

// ✅ Good: Null check before access
const coupon = coupons.find(c => c.id === id);
if (coupon) {
  console.log(coupon.retailer);
}

// ✅ Good: TDD approach
describe('CouponService', () => {
  it('should add a new coupon', async () => {
    // Arrange
    const service = getCouponService();
    const data = { retailer: 'Amazon', initialValue: '50' };

    // Act
    const result = await service.addCoupon(data, 'user-123');

    // Assert
    expect(result.id).toBeDefined();
    expect(result.retailer).toBe('Amazon');
  });
});
</example>

<example type="invalid">
// ❌ Bad: Direct instantiation
import CouponService from '../services/CouponService';
const service = new CouponService();

// ❌ Bad: Implicit any
function processData(data) {
  return data.map(item => item.value);
}

// ❌ Bad: No null check
const coupon = coupons.find(c => c.id === id);
console.log(coupon.retailer);

// ❌ Bad: No TDD, just implementation
const service = getCouponService();
const coupon = await service.addCoupon(data, userId);
// No tests written
</example>
